  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Lloyd Garrison regrets not having seen Mrs. Maria W. Chapman or Caroline [Weston] before leaving Boston. He describes the water cure. Mrs. Chapman will be sorely missed. Garrison writes that &quot;we have few suggestive, creative, executive minds; and such is yours...&quot; He expresses his own indebtedness to her. Sends greetings to George Thompson; fears the sphere of his usefulness as a popular reformer may be limited by election to Parliament. Hopes that Mrs. Chapman will see William H. Ashurst and the Estlins. He sends messages to Elizabeth Pease.</subfield>
